text.tspan: Corel drawing from
Mechanical Engineers
exported as .SVG XML format file
(Scalable Vector Graphics
- open source standard
from the World Wide Web
Consortium - W3C).
Open source, free, Java libraries
Barcode4J generate
our barcodes as SVG XML format files.
Before export, the Object Data Manager
feature of Corel is used to 'tag'
the label elements in SVG,
e.g. the label outline, the visible
rectangles that define where the
barcodes go
on the label
Our in-house Java code, utilising standard off the shelf open source
Apache Batik libaries, will use the tags and co-ordinate data from the
.SVG Corel drawing to extract just the SVG XML needed for the label itself.
Our in-house Java code will then
merge the SVG XML from the resultant label SVG file
with the SVG XML from the barcode file, using the tags and
co-ordinates defined in the SVG label file to position
and scale the barcode SVG XML. There is a tag defined
for each barcode type (e.g. serial number, feature code).
The combined SVG file will be
sent to open source Apache batik
rasterizing program to convert to a
bitmap to send to the label printer
Executive Summary - Benefits over existing system:
- Reliable and Faster:
Complete automation: no manual copying from
Corel/PDF drawing into easy label
- Cost reduction: fewer errors,
- Simpler: No need to manage licenses,
donglessoftware
- Inter-operable: will compliment other projects
Barcode label automation storyboard slide - Rob Davis
document version 1.0 (02 October 2008)
